WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Today is Thursday, July 21, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I'm with Project Biographer John Bishop. We are in Graham'sville, New York at the home of Dr. Emmett and Mrs.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Priscilla Bassett to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Dr. Mrs. Bassett, it's such a pleasure to be here with you. Thank you for the welcome and thank you for agreeing to sit down with us. It's really great to see you.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Thank you.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Let me start with this question. Mrs. Bassett, I was curious in having done some research and preparation of the interview.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:14.000
I was interested in the question of how you came to be interested in the Civil Rights question and progressive politics and causes generally as a young, maybe even adolescent, young woman coming up.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Well, I went to an elementary school in Plainfield, New Jersey, which was as we look back now during the progressive era, Howard Rug or Harold Rug textbooks and just a generally new deal in lightened environment.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:55.000
However, I did come from a Republican family and I left the public school and went to a private school for the last two years of high school.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:19.000
And at that time, during, well, it was 1944, I guess, that Franklin Dono Roosevelt died and one of the classmates came in to school and said, my father danced on the dining room table last night.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:26.000
So that was the conflicting atmospheres that I had in my educational experience.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:45.000
And I did become interested in political issues. I remember going to visit our federal senator, Clifford Case, who was now, he would be an asthma to the Republican leadership.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:59.000
But at any rate, I did have a certain amount of interest, but I was basically a suburban girl whose mother had a very limited appreciation of African American people or culture.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:17.000
My father, a little less so, less extreme than my mother, who was a southerner by birth or by raising, she was raised in the North, but her mother was a southerner and conveyed ideas to her.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So when I went to college, my second year, there was no money. It was at the end of World War II and my father really didn't have a job, so I had to go to work and I went to work at Life Magazine.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:58.000
I had a job, I had a job, I would have been a sophomore in college, I had been there. I was an office girl and I filled the water jugs and sharpened pencils and ran errands and carried coffee and stuff like that.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:22.000
And I met a very articulate and convincing union member and that opened my eyes to quite a few things. So when I returned the next year to Smith, it was a period of a lot of activity and I became involved with the progressive party.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:32.000
We're back after a short break. This is Basie, you were saying about your became interested and began in the involvement of progressive party.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Yes, and of course one of their major concerns was the state of affairs and relationships and the legal systems in the South.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I also was a history major and of course because I was a history major, I pursued a certain amount of studies. There wasn't really, there wasn't any separate black history or African American history or anything in those days, but I managed to find my way to learning.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Oh, and I remember, I remember I had this wonderful book, I forgot that. It was called The Democratic Spirit and it was a collection of all kinds of writers.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:40.000
I have a copy now, I managed to find one again and in it was a poem of county color and that really stuck with me all my life.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Dr. Basie, you grew up near the Virginia North Carolina border.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Yes, it's about 16 miles I think.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Yeah, Henry County.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And I think you lost your father when you were a teenager.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:05.000
He died in 1935, so I would have been by 14 years old when he died.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:29.000
But even by that time, it seems that your, what would become your lifelong path of commitment to the cause of racial equality and progressive change was, was you've even been active by that point as I think I know, say in the effort around the Scottsboro trial.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Yeah, can you describe kind of the nature of life in your family and on your farm and how you got drawn towards that participation?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Well, I can remember before my father died in my first year in high school. He had told me I had some half brothers, two half brothers, and they were 10, 12 years older than I was.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:02.000
And they had, my mother had tried very hard to send them to college.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And the older son, she had sent to Hampton Institute because she had heard that was a great school.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:17.000
But my brother, oh, oh, be die, I guess his name was.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:21.000
He didn't do well there at all.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And fact, she took $500 out of her $1000 insurance that she had insured herself for when her first husband died.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
She wanted to leave something for those seven kids she had.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And that's what she had done and she had done that with the metropolitan life.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
Now, I sat around the house and I listened to what everybody said.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.000
We had no TV and at that time probably no radio. That came later.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:03.000
So I listened to what my mother said that it was good to take half of her money and send in the college.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.000
But he did very poorly at Hampton.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And so the next year she sent him to St. Paul.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And that was in Lawrence, Virginia.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And the reason why she sent him there, he could take some easier course.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And if nothing else, he could study to be a cobbenter.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And a few years later, my other half-brother, Matthew, he went to St. Paul.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.000
I think he finished high school there and did reasonably well.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:58.000
But he came home and he told me that he thought I should go to Lincoln University in Pennsylvania.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And I asked him why did he think I should go there.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
He said, you are a very smart person.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And you aren't in Cleveland, thanks you should come there and go to school.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
And I had two sisters in Cleveland.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And they also told me that they would be willing to get me in high school there.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And I was a little bit nervous about that because the school, elementary school I had gone to,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:39.000
I had probably two teachers out of the 7 or 8 years I was there that finished the year.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And you dropped out with other places and left us without a teacher except somebody who substitute me.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:59.000
I remember, I kind of remember that you got involved with doing civil rights work with the Scottsboro case.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
How did that fit in?

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
Well, I was just talking about a little bit in Henry County before my father died.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
That's what I'm telling you about then.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:22.000
My father had told me already that he thought I was the only one that could run the phone.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.000
I was the whole family. He said, you probably don't know what you can do.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:36.000
Now I had grown up working with my mother in the garden, working with my father in his garden.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And I used to hear them arguing about who's going to take him.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.000
I had another brother about a year and a half older than me.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:52.000
He didn't like bombing at all. He liked no parts of it and didn't want any parts of it.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And I had a younger brother who used to stay at home with my, his name was Milton.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And he was a very good student in school too.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:12.000
So I think he brought my father died. He brought his cousin up.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Her name was Ida Dotson.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And she had gone to school at Chestnut Knob, which is a little bit south of us towards Ridgeway, Chestnut Knob.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And at Chestnut Knob, they had some teacher, I tried to think of his name, but I think his homes and stuff like that.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
He came there as principal from Pennsylvania.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
And he was a teacher my father had gone to.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:51.000
And this teacher, Ida Dotson, had gone to him too.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
So she felt I was a very smart student.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:02.000
And she transferred me from fifth grade to seventh grade.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:12.000
And it became a very hostile school for me because I had boys, 14 and 15 and 16 and some up as much as 17 and 18.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:18.000
And they didn't like me being in that class and they were very hostile.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:26.000
But I guess that's the only place I felt like I had to take her gone to school to protect myself.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:40.000
Was it your father's example or your mother too that inspired your willingness to step forward to contribute in civil rights cases and causes?

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:50.000
Yeah, my mother thought it was a good idea that we shouldn't just accept things coming from people.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And we ran into a lot of problems right there at home because there was white families that at Merd,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
see when they got the field they are caught in the accompaniment.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
And they got the Bassett Furniture Company.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:14.000
You had white people moving from Georgia, North Carolina, South Carolina,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
and maybe Tennessee, a few from Tennessee.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And the Bassett, the white Bassett and my grandfather was given to the Bassett's father when he married a daughter.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:55.000
He married a daughter of the Staples who, now, Turner's, I got the wrong name, Turner.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:00.000
That was who my grandfather was raised by and he was a Turner.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
But he stayed with the Bassett's.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
They didn't put him out in the little house of his own.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
My key lived at the Turner's.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
They put him in with that two boys, maybe three.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
I'm not sure, but it was two at least.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And he slept with them and he didn't go to schools that they went to.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:33.000
He didn't go to any school at all because at that time there were no school for blacks.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:41.000
But these two brothers, so I understand, I got this from them and from my father.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:49.000
They used to come home and teach him math and teach him whatever history that they had learned about in school.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:59.000
So my grandfather picked that up and according to what some of those families told me, the Bassett's,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:05.000
that he knew more and more history than his two sons did.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So they made him the boss of one's sawmill of what maybe it was two, I'm not sure.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:22.000
But these sawmills saw the lumber and they shipped it to Grand Srapitz, Michigan.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:30.000
They shipped logs that for a while and later on they started to ship in the timber there that they saw.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:40.000
Now William Henry was in charge of all of this and he was in charge of a lot of white people.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:49.000
Now it turns out and this has leaked all the way through to me as a kid that

00:15:49.000 --> 00:16:01.000
the Bassett's were going to get $6 million from the continental bank of Chicago to build a furniture factory.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.000
But he had to get the approval of the state of Virginia.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:14.000
Now the state of Virginia say in 1900 about then,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:21.000
wanted no blacks, Boston, anybody, not even blacks.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:26.000
So they got rid of William Henry.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:31.000
So he was eager to become a preacher and I assume he did.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:36.000
He married a lot of people to the Virginia. I looked at all of that.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:44.000
He had somebody to marry almost every week when he was a preacher.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:49.000
So he had to give up his job.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Well my father, I don't know how this worked out,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:03.000
but he worked for another family named Tillesta, who ran the Furniture Company.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:14.000
He was told essentially about the same thing because they were getting ready to build a furniture store that

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:22.000
would manufacture windows and all of those things.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So he had to build a factory kind of too.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:33.000
So he got his factory, but he said my father had to give up his job too.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:41.000
So those things had impacted me all my life because I used to listen to them talk.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And sometimes they didn't realize I knew what they were talking about, but it did.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And I remember all the names they associated with.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:18:05.000
But I never heard the lester say anything about that until I came back from the University of Massachusetts.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Now that must have been 20 years later that I had gone up there and got a master's degree.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:26.000
And I came home and I had a sister who had worked in the hospital on the war year.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
And she had gone around to see sick patients.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And sometimes she saw whites that she knew and she stopped to see them.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:41.000
And she found out that one of these women knew my father.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And she said, well, I'd like for your brother a one of John's sons I'd like to talk with me.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Now I came home, I guess it was Christmas or something.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And she said, would you go by to see this woman?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
I said, now who is she?

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
She says she's a cousin of Pop.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Now I never knew that Pop was a cousin to Tillester's wife.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
I never knew that.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:22.000
My father, usually when he had a conversation like that, he got out of my hearing.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
My distance.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:35.000
So I talked with my sister and I said, you know, this woman is still alive.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.000
My father has been dead for a long time.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.000
What did she do for him when he was alive?

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
And why should I go and talk with?

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:48.000
I just couldn't go.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:53.000
And you say about the Scottsboro?

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:03.000
Well, I guess I was a freshman in high school when I began to read and hear a lot about the Scottsboro.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And to me they were about my age and there were white people around us.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:17.000
And we used to be one of the biggest pawns to go swimming.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:30.000
We used to take the horses, the drag plane, and make a dam across this little stream that ran down from the Moises place.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
And we used to make a huge pawn there.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So everybody that lived in that neighborhood because white and black came by and saw that lovely pawn, wanted to go swimming.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.000
Now we didn't use swimming suits.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:51.000
And the women came in, they would go up a stream, jump in, and swim.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So that was this man, I assume, he was my mother's first god.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
He was a Moise.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:17.000
And he came by with his daughter and another cousin who was one of his sister's child, girls, I should say.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
I guess they were 12, 14 about the same as the ages of.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:24.000
And they wanted to go swimming.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:31.000
And they brought that father, we didn't understand why she had brought him, why they had brought him.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:38.000
But I guess they brought him to teach him a lesson that they could go swimming with us and there was nothing wrong with it.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:43.000
They knew, we knew, they knew that we were cousins.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:49.000
My mother and her father were first god.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And I guess we weren't supposed to know that, but we did.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
And we told them as much.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:04.000
And my mother was also first cousin to his wife.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:09.000
So I said, Mom, he must have married a cousin.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.000
She said, yes, he did.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:18.000
And I knew my mother first marriage was with someone that was related to her.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:23.000
Well, he was the first cousin of the second, I'm not sure, but he was a cousin.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:28.000
So I asked my mother at that stage, why would you marry a cousin?

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
Why did you ask him?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
Was he your cousin?

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
She said he didn't know.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
And I didn't know.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
So we made a mistake.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:46.000
So we used to tell them about that could be nothing between us and them because we were first cousins.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And that's the reason we got some kind of people a little bit crazy in this family already.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:58.000
So I told them all about that.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:05.000
So this man came along with the two girls and they brought him, they said, well, you can go talk with him.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
So he came and talked with me.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
And he talked for a long time.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.000
So I told him, yes, they could go up there, jump in the water, they could swim.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:20.000
We're not going to grab them and try to hug them, they are cousin.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:25.000
So eventually he says, well, go ahead.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And the daughters had told him before then that he should go home.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:37.000
If he could stand and look at them swim, we're going home.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:40.000
And you won't have to look at her.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:43.000
He just went out in the woods, a short distance.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.000
And I could just see him out, catch him on the speak.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:50.000
I don't know what else he was doing.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:58.000
But at the end he came back to pick up his daughters and he thanked me for letting them swim.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:07.000
And I don't remember much after that because I think that nation here, my father might have died.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:13.000
And I think my full time work was taking care of the poem.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:14.000
Sure.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:18.000
And Mirka Nikao and doing things like that.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:22.000
And going to high school, when I could.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Mrs. Bassa, we'll come back and this is the one of these interviews where we should back and forth.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:33.000
Mrs. Bassa, can you talk to Bassa, you mentioned you're getting the master's up at University of Massachusetts.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:37.000
I think it's in that context that the two of you met.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:44.000
And I wondered Mrs. Bassa, if you would recall the circumstances and how you two came to know each other.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Well, this was after World War II.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:57.000
And I went to a women's college, Smith College, in Northampton, Massachusetts.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And there was a road that ran from Northampton to Amherst.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:06.000
And along that road, there was what was called a roadhouse in those days.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:14.000
And this roadhouse became rather notorious because they refused to serve blacks.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:21.000
So some of the Smith women went over to join a picket line.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:30.000
And whether this is apocryphal or whether that is really the first time we met,

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:33.000
that's what I remember.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And then there was a lawsuit because some people were arrested.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:45.000
I was not arrested. I seemed to have a knack for not getting arrested sometimes.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:52.000
And so I was a witness at the trial, but you know, when the people, you were not arrested either.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
No. No.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:59.000
Anyway, we got to see one another again after that.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:06.000
And we had friends in Amherst where we were welcome to go for dinner and so forth.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:14.000
So your knowledge of that protest would have come through the progressive party community, student group?

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:17.000
Or how would you have known about that to be to go into that?

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
It could have been. Yes.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:29.000
Because I know our lawyer, the lawyer, that, and he was very careful not to broom me for this when I had to be a witness.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:37.000
He said, I'm not, you know, you just remember yourself just what happened to help because I'm not putting any words in your mouth.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.000
And of course, I had never done it before.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:46.000
And I went to see the president of a college and told him that I was going to be a witness.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:51.000
And he said, that's fine. That's what you should be doing.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:59.000
So perhaps it was through the, I know the lawyer was part of the progressive party.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.000
Yeah. And I wanted to ask too, at Smith in those years, there would have been what?

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:06.000
Just maybe a half dozen, half an American students.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
I have to give that.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
A half dozen would be a lot. Yeah.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
Yeah. Four, three, four.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
There were four years of college.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And in my class, I was in two classes, you know, as there.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
And there were certainly never more than two or three.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:25.000
Yeah.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Would that have been your first occasion to become directly impersonately acquainted with half Americans?

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.000
Or had you in?

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Oh, in my school.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.000
Yeah.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:41.000
I do remember that the atmosphere was very supportive of the black students.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
You mean at Smith or?

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
No. At the public school.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:46.000
In Plainfield.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
In Plainfield, New Jersey.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:51.000
There are Plainfields.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:59.000
We lived in a part of Plainfield that was all white, but there was a small enclave of black families

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:05.000
who were mainly working domestics in the households.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.000
And they were in this classes with us.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:21.000
And there was, you know, to my, well, what, five, six grade self, I didn't see that the teachers, you know, did any.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
Treated them any differently.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:28.000
And in the eighth grade, we had a contata.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And we sang, uh, Ballad for Americans.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:40.000
And the, uh, Paul Robson's part was played by one of the black students.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
And of course, he was the star.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:45.000
And Paul Robson did come to Plainfield.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:50.000
And he performed at the public library.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:53.000
No, no, at the public high school.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:58.000
And that was a really very impressive experience.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
And I attended.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
What students are with your family?

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
It's possible my brother went along, but not my parents.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:10.000
The earlier I mentioned your mother had some.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Let me ask this too.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And as you acted two of you in Met and began to become interested in one another, how did you,

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:24.000
I mean, it's obviously a very challenging context for an eracial couple in that era.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:31.000
How did you think about those issues and find your way forward in a context that could be even,

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:36.000
not just unfriendly, but even hostile sometimes?

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:37.000
How about that, Anne?

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
Why?

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:53.000
Well, uh, you know, I don't remember anybody up at the University of, um,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:30:00.000
of Massachusetts being hostile about seeing us together over at the University.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:10.000
Now, I have a suspicion that over at her dormitory, I guess I only went by there a couple of times.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:13.000
I remember going more than that.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:18.000
I never went to that party that the woman said she danced with me.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:22.000
Well, there was a house mother.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:23.000
Yeah.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
But she took it in stride.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:34.000
She had had a really big uproar the year before because a student had become pregnant.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:46.000
And that was monumental for the house mother and for the student who supposedly didn't know what had happened.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:51.000
And anyway, you know, this was not a very enlightened period.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:31:02.000
But I, you know, we just felt that it was our right and privilege if we cared for each other to proceed.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:09.000
I guess we knew that, you know, we might encounter some hostility and,

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:12.000
uh, personal hostility.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
I don't remember that at Smith.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:15.000
No.

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:16.000
Yeah.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:23.000
Dr. Bassett, let me take you back to, um, to your move to Tuskegee to enter college.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:29.000
And you would have a range of it sounds like a very, very interesting experience as well as student there.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:34.000
And then the course would go on into military service.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:35.000
Yeah.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:45.000
But before we get to the Second World War, I'd be interested if you would kind of share some recollections of your experiences at Tuskegee.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:58.000
Well, at Tuskegee, I was in, uh, went there as a work study into a work study program.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.000
I was going to work.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:08.000
I think it was, may have been 24 hours a week, or may have been a little longer than that.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:17.000
And I think at some time I gave that up and made it a little shorter because I didn't want to be there for five years.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:20.000
I wanted to try to graduate in four years.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:23.000
So I was trying to take a fuller load.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:31.000
But that was very difficult because I had to get up at four o'clock in the morning, go milk the cow.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:35.000
And I think I had 13 cows in the milk.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.000
And they were all gurns of cows.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:44.000
He put me over there and he used to come around and take a look at me milking this.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:47.000
We were milking my hand at that time.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:51.000
And he says, where did you learn to milk the cow?

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:56.000
He said, we had cows at home and I milked two or three cows all the time there.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
So that's where I learned to milk cows.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
So I'm milking here.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:05.000
He used to go around after me to see what any milk was being left in the cow's back.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:10.000
I said, no, I make sure that everything is done properly.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:14.000
We did it at home and I'm not doing anything new here.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:20.000
I wash her up with the teats and make sure they clean.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:23.000
And oh, there was a wash man.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
I think he did it before I didn't have to do that.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
So I milked these 13 cows.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:35.000
And that was about, I guess, there were three other people that milked their whole steams,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:39.000
which took a little longer and they gave her a little more milk.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And just to kind of situate this for the interview, these were, this was part of the school's program.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:48.000
This was part of the school.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:53.000
And I think it paid her something like 15 to 20 cents an hour, some place, isn't it?

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
That's what it was.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
We didn't get much money for that.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:08.000
And so I had to do some extra jobs on weekend, like cleaning up the lots where the cows were fed

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:11.000
doing the winter months especially.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:16.000
And I used to do that.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:23.000
And sometimes there were people who had other new jobs that they would give to me,

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
like a barbecue or something.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:29.000
I used to stay up all night, helping them hand barbecue.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:35.000
And they called me because Tuskegee were going to have a big feast.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:40.000
One day a year, they invited the whole community around.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:49.000
And they just cooked a lot of horn meat on the, they went out in the woods and they dug a trench.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:54.000
And they put some basil and some stones around.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
And we stayed there all night.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:02.000
And I'd get paid for all night too because he would sleep some and I would sleep some.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:10.000
And this man had this song that he used to sing to me, that he did all of this for white people too.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
You wanted me to know that.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
He said, they certainly have been good to me.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:19.000
I said, how good, stay up all night cooking their meat.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
Is that good?

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.000
You get a little tired sometimes.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
So he just laughed and went home.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
But he did show me.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:35.000
He made up all of the salt and pepper and everything.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:38.000
And he put that in some kind of that.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:44.000
And he'd go over to meet everyone so I would sit there and put it on to me.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.000
So I did learn all of those things.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
So I did that for the first two years.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.000
And it was tough.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:57.000
I think I got ayes in math and ayes in a few other things.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
But there were some courses.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.000
I think biochemistry.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
I think I got an A in that.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:08.000
And the man came to me and he pleaded with me.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:10.000
He could give me a job there.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
It would be much easier.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.000
And I could mage in biochemistry.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:19.000
But I kept thinking about the farm back home.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
I don't know.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
My father's expecting me to run that.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
By that time he was dead.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:31.000
And my family still depends on me when you run the farm.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:39.000
I had been able to bring in another black person from a white farm.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.000
And he worked for this man.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
I think he got 75 cents a day.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:46.000
We told him we could pay him $2 a day.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Because we traded so stuff every weekend in town,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
at the on the street.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.000
And we made some money.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:00.000
Enough to pay him $2 an hour whenever he had to.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
So we had him.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:06.000
So he just gave up his job with this white family.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:09.000
And he came to work with us.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And he almost looked at us as if we were his children.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Me and my younger brother.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
We were it.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:24.000
And the other brothers were into their building business,

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
or plumbing business, and so forth.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
Excuse me.

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:32.000
What was that?

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.000
Next job.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
Okay, we're back after a short break.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:36.000
In YA.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:37.000
That was it.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:40.000
Wasn't it the National Use Administration?

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:41.000
Use the Administration.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:42.000
That money.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.000
The Roseville Administration gave me.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
Okay, hold it.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:48.000
I think we're good.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:49.000
We're back.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.000
We're back on.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:51.000
Thank you.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.000
Yeah, I can go.

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:54.000
Okay.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:58.000
Yeah, they gave me a scholarship.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:03.000
And that is, I think it was supposed to be $25 a month.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.000
That was twice what I was making working.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:11.000
And I only worked at Dr. Carlos Place for about 12 years.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
12 hours a week.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
Usually by two hours, every other day or something like that.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
And maybe a little more on Saturday and Sunday.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
Showing visitors around.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:24.000
Yeah.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.000
So that was very easy.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:31.000
Now just how I got there, I've never been able to find out.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:36.000
But I used to have a man at the Labor Department.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.000
And he was a writer.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000
Now what was his name?

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:43.000
Ralph Ellison.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:44.000
Ralph Ellison.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.000
Oh, yeah, he's one of him.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:47.000
Yeah.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:56.000
He told me that he was going to take care of me.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:01.000
I told him I was working more hours than I've been painful.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:04.000
Because if I worked extra time over at the moment,

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:07.000
they didn't want to pay me for it.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:12.000
So when I got this job, I didn't have to worry about that anymore.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.000
And I had more time to study.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.000
And I got to meet Dr. Carva.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:25.000
And I worked with his post-doc that was one of his assistants.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:28.000
Let me ask, how did that come to Dr. Carva at just a moment?

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.000
How did you come to meet Ralph Ellison?

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:35.000
Well, he was at Tuskegee for some reason.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
And he was working in that department.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:41.000
And I used to go by there.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:47.000
But I didn't realize to later that he had written the book.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:48.000
Much later.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:49.000
Much later.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:50.000
Yeah.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:51.000
I put it together.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
That's who I was talking to.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:54.000
And I'm talking to.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:55.000
But I never knew.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:56.000
Yeah.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And how about Dr. Carva?

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:01.000
What was the experience like of being a dick?

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:09.000
Was he someone that you could have a fairly close, personal academic context relationship with?

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:16.000
Or was he someone who had such stature that there was a distance between him and his students?

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:23.000
I don't think he ever had that distance between me and one other fellow that worked there.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:26.000
Two of us got those scholarship.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:35.000
We used to, when we first get the work, he wanted to see us for about a half hour.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
Just sit and talk.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:41.000
And I remember, I was just beginning to grow a little bit.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:46.000
And he used to take his hands and all fill it across the...

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:51.000
You just like a little spring chicken.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Just growing up.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:41:01.000
And so I, you know, asked this, my supervisor, you know, why does he do that?

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And he told me, now, this...

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:07.000
I got to, you know, my...

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:12.000
I haven't seen it written down that he was...

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:17.000
Well, I should've said, castrated as a young baby.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:23.000
Because they wanted him to be a wagon driver.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:34.000
Now, so he felt that was the reason he had never grown a bit himself.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:39.000
He had a few whiskers around here, but I don't think he even shaved.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:44.000
And he says, because he was castrated as a young kid.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:47.000
So, very sad.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:50.000
What did you do about it?

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:55.000
And I think at that stage, he was about 70 years old.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:58.000
I think he died at 71 or 2.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.000
And I think I had just gone home.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:07.000
And I had a picture I was going to stop by there the next time I went down the Toskey

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
and get his autograph.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:14.000
But before I got back to that, he stood.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:21.000
How did you make the determination as you were completing your college years?

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:27.000
How did you navigate the choice between the responsibility of perhaps going back to take over the farm?

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:30.000
Or going off for graduate school?

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.000
Of course, the war would intervene, but also...

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
Yeah, the war did intervene.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:37.000
How did you make that choice to...

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:41.000
You kind of made for me with the army and all of that.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:44.000
Because I had already signed up.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:48.000
I think I've gotten a couple of letters from them.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:53.000
That, you know, they're things that you can volunteer for, and you won't be drafted.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And that was the Toskey Army Air Force.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:00.000
That they were establishing then.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:06.000
And I was, I think, 18 when they started after me.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:15.000
And I wrote my mother a long letter that she would have to approve of me going into this.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:23.000
And that was another option I had was to go to Fort Valley after I finished college.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:30.000
And if I did volunteer there to become an Army officer, they could...

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
I could go there for...

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:35.000
I mean, it was six months or it was 90 days.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
I don't remember what it was.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
But I could take that.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
That was another option.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:46.000
And another option was go someplace in Texas and become a war officer.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
But that was trained into that.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
I could volunteer for that.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:55.000
So I wrote my mother and told her those were the options I had.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:59.000
And would she approve of that?

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
She wrote me back a long letter.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:05.000
I proven she says, I think you know what you want to do.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:09.000
And I think you know more about it than I do.

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:22.000
But I want to tell you this, that nobody in our family who ever volunteered for the Army came home.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
They all got killed.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:30.000
Now, I had to stop and think about that because she put down some name.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:33.000
That was an Uncle Willie.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:37.000
I said, my mom, I never heard of an Uncle Willie.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:44.000
So he must have been your brother because no, he was my uncle, my great uncle.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:53.000
He went to the Alamo out in Texas.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:57.000
And he was killed there.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:04.000
But Uncle Willie, I'm talking about somebody who looked like me.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:09.000
She says, no, he looked more white than he did like.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
And he went out there and he was killed there.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:15.000
But he's still young.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:19.000
And then she went, remember what his last name was?

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:20.000
Ovidaya.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:22.000
No.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:23.000
Ovidaya.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:24.000
Oh, Willie.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:25.000
Travis.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
He was killed at the Alamo.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:32.000
You can read that in history books, but they never say that he was black.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:40.000
I don't know that he was either because one of these grandmother's back there were supposed to be white.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.000
I'm not sure about that.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:46.000
And different fathers.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:47.000
Different fathers.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:48.000
Yes.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:49.000
Yeah.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:51.000
Yeah.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:46:01.000
So, were you, in the end, what was your decision about whether or not to anyone who segregated armed forces as a volunteer?

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
Well, I never wanted to hurt a prison.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:11.000
And that's what I'd had a couple of people who had gone that route was going to prison.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:12.000
That's a D.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:13.000
You know, why?

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:14.000
This stuff, you're drafted.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:15.000
No.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:16.000
Oh.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.000
Before I was drafted.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:20.000
I had a bunch of conscientious objectors went to prison.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:21.000
Yeah.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:22.000
Went to prison.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:24.000
The only ones I knew went to prison.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
And I didn't want to go to prison.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:31.000
So, I went to my draft board in Maudenzville.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:38.000
And, you know, they had the Maudenzville 7, and Maudenzville.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:41.000
I was away at that time.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:44.000
I probably at the University of Massachusetts, probably.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:51.000
Now, you're getting your time mixed up here because the draft was before you went to Massachusetts.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:52.000
Yeah.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:53.000
Before you went in the army.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:54.000
Yeah.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:59.000
But you'll get to that later, the Maudenzville 7.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:02.000
Well, I'm not going to get into that.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:08.000
The only thing I'm saying that one of the members of the draft board was Whittle.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And Whittle was the judge.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
On the draft board.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:21.000
And there was a couple of other people that lived around that was running a dairy farm.

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:29.000
So, I was telling them that, you know, I've already kind of, you know, talked with a man that his son is going away to the army.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:36.000
And I could buy the his ten cows and I could go into a dairy business myself.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:50.000
And he and I guess the whole group, that says, well, you know, we haven't such a poor turnout of blacks who are pale and the physical.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:55.000
And so, you're in good shape.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
So, we want to draft you.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:05.000
I said, you want to draft me because somebody else, I said, you have more to do with that than I do.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:07.000
You know, they work for you.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:14.000
Some of these people that got a draft, I got a deferment, work for you.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:17.000
Two members Brad showing the other one I knew.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
And I told them so.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:22.000
So, I don't have anybody to work for you.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:29.000
I've never worked for anybody that my grand fathers or fathers worked for.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.000
So, I just told them that.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:37.000
They just looked at each other and they tell my answer to me.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:44.000
After this experience with draft, ultimately you would go, I think, into the quartermaster core.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:48.000
Yeah, I went to the quartermaster core.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:58.000
And in there, I ran and I don't know how I guess it can't be.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:03.000
I went to a special outfit that count me.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:12.000
After I finished my whatever course that they taught you that, there was two courses.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:20.000
One being a soldier and the other one by the quartermaster core.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:25.000
I took both of those and I made very high grades and all of that.

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:48.000
And they sent me, when I finished, to Company E, which was the essentially the company that most of the people that were controlled by, let me see, Colonel Snowden, who was black.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:53.000
He was the highest-ranking black officer at Company.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:58.000
So, I went to work for him.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:03.000
And I was called up several times.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:07.000
I don't know why, that they had a new job for me.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:14.000
And once I went to a meeting, I guess there was a thousand people there.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:17.000
They were all white.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:23.000
I walked up to the front and took a seat.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
And that was a young woman there.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
I guess from Petersburg.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:33.000
She walked over and says, would I go and sit in the back seat?

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
So, I just said to her.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:40.000
I said, if you don't want me here, why don't you just tell me to go outside?

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:48.000
You put me in the back and she looked at me and I walked on the outside.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:54.000
And ten minutes later, a young officer who probably was white, he was white.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:57.000
No, then me came out of the garden.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:51:01.000
But they never told me what they were, why I was called up there.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
There was all white.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:04.000
Nothing.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
I saw no black.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:12.000
I was just a second.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:15.000
Okay, we're back.

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:24.000
Any memories in part to, I'm sure many do, but are there memories that you would like to share concerning your military service?

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:35.000
I'm thinking of the experience of, as was so commonly reported by black servicemen who served in second world war.

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:41.000
It's this profound irony of fighting, quote, on behalf of freedom.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:49.000
And across the Atlantic Ocean, then you come back to return to life in a sharply segregated society.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:52:03.000
Just wondering if there are, if the experience of fighting in a segregated armed forces altered, adjusted, shifted your perspectives about race relations in the United States?

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.000
Or were they?

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:25.000
Well, I just stayed in Camp Lea and I stayed in company E and most of the people there were professors, some of them were college presidents, some of them were all kinds of professional people.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:28.000
That's mostly who I was around.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:31.000
And I used to go into work there.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:46.000
And I guess I found out more about this company when I met up Teller who was woman with me at the time, named Robert Mane, in my N.G.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:47.000
You were turning?

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
He was an attorney.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:54.000
And he was, I think, arguably the case before the Supreme Court.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.000
And he went to AP Hill.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:01.000
We had to go up there every, I think, maybe about every six months.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
I would have to go.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.000
And sometimes we would go that together, Mane.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:18.000
And at the last time, there was a big stir in France about some soldiers getting extreme punishment.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
This is that or the other.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:25.000
And they gave Robert Mane a captain.

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:28.000
Or maybe they gave him a colonel or something.

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:39.000
And he was shipped to Europe to help rectify some of these mistreatment that blacks were complaining about there in France.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:46.000
So he asked me, he says, you never come down.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:49.000
Everybody there wants to be known.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:53.000
And they want to be known by the officers that was a captain.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:57.000
That was a person of a tenor, a second lieutenant.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:04.000
And maybe I think somebody else there that I knew.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:08.000
But I never went down to talk with any of them.

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:14.000
The only thing that I did was just report from my work and do it.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:18.000
Go home, go back to my room.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:21.000
So they seemed to have liked that.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:30.000
But he told me Mane did that everybody is around trying to build themselves up.

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:36.000
So there was a second lieutenant there.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:39.000
He didn't like me at all.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
And I never had much to say to them.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
And he didn't have much to say to me.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:47.000
So one day I ended up at AP Hill with him in charge.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:53.000
And he told me when I got back to the company, he was going to have me.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:57.000
I was a sergeant, he was going to make me a private again.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:00.000
I said, what? But what?

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:05.000
He says, you are not doing all the things I'm telling you.

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
I said, well, I'll tell you.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:11.000
And I haven't broken in your rules as far as I know.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:15.000
So he went back and told the Colonel that.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.000
And the Colonel just, I was told just like that.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:23.000
And he said, you must have put both him somewhere.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:30.000
And he said anything to you because he never said anything to me.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:36.000
After the war, what drove your decision to apply to the University of Massachusetts?

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:39.000
How did you reach that?

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:44.000
Well, as far as I could see, I came out of the arm.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:48.000
I got a job teaching agriculture in the county.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:53.000
And I was liking that job reasonably well.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
You know, you've got a car.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:58.000
You've got about $90 a month.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:02.000
And most people around was making 60 or 70 a month.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:05.000
I got a little more money than they did.

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:07.000
I worked 12 months in the year.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:10.000
And it was kind of interesting.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:17.000
But after two years, and there were more people coming home from the Army.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:28.000
And that was a part of the county extended down to Washington.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:32.000
Virginia is going, the road going to Dan'sville.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:39.000
58 went right through Washington, Virginia.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:51.000
And there were some big plantations down there.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:59.000
And there were a couple of bankers who were establishing,

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:07.000
they were establishing some kind of a program for blacks returning from the Army

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:17.000
that they could study agriculture and go to school on their plantation.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:21.000
And I was supposed to be the teacher.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:25.000
He says, the superintendent had approved that.

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:28.000
But I'd never approved of it.

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:32.000
And the only thing I could see that this would work out for them.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:35.000
They were going to get $75 a month.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:43.000
And these farm were going to get some of this government money to pay for this school

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:46.000
that they were going to have on the plantation.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:51.000
So I was supposed to be in charge of that.

00:57:51.000 --> 00:58:00.000
So I just told them one day that I could never be a person that's training somebody to be a sharecropper.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.000
And that's the only thing.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:07.000
After three years, this program was going to run out.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:09.000
And what were they going to do?

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:18.000
And they would be on the farmer's land in his house with three or four kids probably, maybe two.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:20.000
Maybe just one, maybe none.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:25.000
But anyway, they would be stuck on that plantation for the rest of us.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:27.000
I told my just couldn't do that.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:32.000
I told two bankers, and they owned huge plantation.

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:37.000
Probably thousands of bankers have land lots of the back.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:42.000
And all the farmers I saw were black.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:50.000
It's interesting when we went with Julian Bond in the footsteps of the Civil Rights Movement tour.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:54.000
We met a young white professor from a school.

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:57.000
He was from a college in the South.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:58.000
From Mississippi.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:01.000
And he knew about that program.

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:07.000
Emmett had never known anybody else who knew anything about that program.

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:09.000
But he was right.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:18.000
Let me ask you, after you met Maryden in 1950,

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:24.000
you both would move together to Columbus, Ohio, as you pursued your graduate work.

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:31.000
And I'm interested in experiences of you had in Columbus,

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:34.000
and you would continue your efforts in civil rights.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:39.000
And also, let me ask you, and maybe as you describe some of that time there,

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:47.000
I wonder too, if any early stirrings of considerations of women's status and issues played in your mind,

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:51.000
have you ever been touched up against your life at that point at all?

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:57.000
Well, that really came out in retrospect, I guess.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:03.000
But we first went to New York, and we're there for a couple of years.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:11.000
And I had wanted to go to law school, but that didn't work out.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:17.000
Because by then, I guess I'd been kind of sidetracked because of Emmett.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:22.000
But also, there was no money for me to go to graduate school.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:26.000
So I got a job with the New York Public Library as an intern.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:31.000
And it was a wonderful program, an excellent program.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:40.000
But this was putting me into women's work, library, nursing, school teacher.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:50.000
But I must say that it wasn't traded with a lot of regret, because at that point.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.000
Right, that's one of those things.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:56.000
Back in Abrish, was Walnie Nelson and Juanita Nelson?

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:00.000
Were Walnie and Juanita Nelson and Abrish when you were there?

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:03.000
Walnie and Anita Nelson.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:05.000
Did you know?

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:07.000
I heard about it a while back then.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:09.000
Why?

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Nelson.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Walnie Nelson.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.000
You know, they must have come later.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.000
Yeah.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:17.000
Okay.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:22.000
So going...

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:27.000
The women's movement didn't...

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:33.000
I mean, it was very clear to me that there were these patterns that you were supposed to follow.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:40.000
And of course, I was already not following one of the big ones.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:50.000
So when we got to Columbus, I went to work in the library there.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:56.000
And I found out through a neighbor that I could get a job at General Motors

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:59.000
and make much, much more money.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.000
And so I did.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:05.000
And that was, of course, women's work also.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:09.000
Although I was on the production line,

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:12.000
there was all women in those positions.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:20.000
The skilled tradesmen were men and predominant, almost exclusively white.

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:24.000
But there were...

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:29.000
There were black women working on the production line.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:33.000
But I'll just tell you a small story about that.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:41.000
When I first went to be interviewed for the job to apply for the General Motors job,

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:47.000
I sat next to some people in the waiting room and a black woman,

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:50.000
when I asked her, did she know anything about buses?

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:53.000
I don't know how I got there, but anyway...

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:55.000
I think I might have just taken that.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:56.000
Did we...

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:57.000
We didn't have a car.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:59.000
Maybe you borrowed one.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:02.000
But anyway, she said, well, I'll take you into town,

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:07.000
and then you can get a bus up to the college, university.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:13.000
So I did, and I got to be friends with her.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:18.000
But before that happened, before we really became friends,

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:24.000
I went back to work, and I went into the washroom.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:29.000
And there was this black woman, and she looked very much like the woman

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:34.000
that I had been helped out by.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:37.000
But she looked different because she had a wig on.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:42.000
And that always threw me when people would change wigs and stuff like that.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:46.000
So anyway, I thought, well, if I don't speak to her,

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:50.000
she'll say, oh, these white women, they're all the same thing.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:57.000
And if I do speak to her, she'll think that I think all black women look the same.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:59.000
I don't really...

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:02.000
But I said, oh, with that, I'm going to say hi.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:07.000
And I said hi, and we had a nice friendship after that.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:17.000
But she was on probation for 90 days before she could get a job on the production line.

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:22.000
And so she worked in the washroom during that period.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:29.000
And she had worked in Curtis Wright factory during World War II.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:32.000
She had real factory experience.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:37.000
I had worked a couple of months in a spiral...

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:46.000
...sperry gyroscope factory in Plainfield grinding lenses.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:51.000
So I had no... you know, that wasn't anything much.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:55.000
But she was experienced, and this was the way they played.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:01.000
Well, I became active in the union after that, because I said that's got to stop.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:04.000
Not that it stopped, but, you know...

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:07.000
And you would have... you would...

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:10.000
...soon... effectively in the role of a shop steward, as I understand it.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:11.000
Yes, I was.

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:14.000
Yeah, and that was very unusual.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:21.000
Years later, the daughter of a friend of mine who is active in the UAW said,

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:26.000
there weren't any women stewards, and I said, oh, yes, there were.

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:28.000
And I was it.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:30.000
But that was in that plant.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:32.000
I don't know what went on everywhere else.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:35.000
And you can tell me if this is correct or not.

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:40.000
It sounds as if experiences like that would have confirmed your sense of...

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:43.000
...justice, injustice.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:46.000
Rather than altered it, you mentioned the redness of the redness of the confirmed and deepened it, maybe?

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:52.000
They confirmed it, and they also gave me the sense that I could do something about it.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:06:00.000
And that's really been the guiding light that you don't just sit back and let it happen.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:07.000
Even though I must say, I don't think we've gotten very far, but I still...

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:10.000
I have hope.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:13.000
You were in Columbus in 1954.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.000
Yes, we were.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:17.000
When the Browns and the Cedric came down.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:19.000
Browns and Cedric came down.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:27.000
Of course, and then, of course, the late summer of 55 is the horrible experience with the till murder.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:40.000
And I know Dr. Berth that you made an effort to raise money for Emmett Till's mother.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:45.000
We had a big meeting at one of the Baptist Church.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:48.000
I think we raised $3,000.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:55.000
And there were some people who felt we shouldn't have sent it all to her because she was...

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:58.000
Well, I don't know.

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:04.000
They just felt that she was just going to not use it wisely as all I could see.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:09.000
But I didn't see anything wrong with giving it to her.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:12.000
She had gone through it, no?

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:16.000
And you also went out in the park and collected money there?

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:22.000
Yeah, we collected money down at the state capital.

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:25.000
That's where the restrictions were taken.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:29.000
Yeah, you're alluding to there was an article coverage of your effort to raise that money in the crisis.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:31.000
The end of the city.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:32.000
Yeah.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:39.000
Did your effort in a public context like that in Columbus in the mid-50s?

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:44.000
Did that cause you any problems inside your academic program?

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:46.000
I guess so.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:50.000
I guess so because...

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:54.000
You know, when I was getting ready to...

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:57.000
I guess I was about ready to get graduated.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:05.000
And I was teaching...

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:14.000
They decided that I hadn't had any teaching experience since I had been at Ohio State.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:22.000
They wanted to give me some because they had just gotten a report that most students who

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:30.000
do well on their qualifying exam have had some teaching experience because you learned

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:33.000
things and learned well when you're teaching.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:37.000
So they decided I should teach a course.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:44.000
So I taught a course and after I finished teaching this course,

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:53.000
two of the students who took this course on the me and another fellow,

01:08:53.000 --> 01:09:02.000
I think his name was Kenneth Fox, but it doesn't mean too much.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:04.000
I don't think he's still alive.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:11.000
He died and he was a very talented and a very honest person.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:17.000
And I think he had gone to Uppsala because I went to Uppsala a year.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:21.000
And I think he's the one that encouraged me to go there too.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:24.000
So I thought he was a very nice fellow.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:38.000
The thing that bothered me since I had these two students and I was going through

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:47.000
Chicago, I gone there several times and every place who wanted me sent me a ticket to fly

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:54.000
up, kept me in the best hotel, the Palmer House or whatever, the Hilton House or whatever

01:09:54.000 --> 01:10:02.000
it was, had those places for two weeks to look for jobs in Chicago.

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:11.000
And they all said, if they hired me, the whole top would go off of that building.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:14.000
That's what they said.

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:25.000
The man at, let me see what was that, and the name of the company, it was human.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:28.000
Real lemon?

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:31.000
No, no, no, real lemon, all of the ginger.

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:34.000
Oh no, no, they don't.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:37.000
That was, oh.

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:41.000
I can pick that up.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:44.000
I have it written down in there.

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:45.000
It's something like...

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:46.000
Deatrous food.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:48.000
Deatrous food.

01:10:48.000 --> 01:10:49.000
Yeah.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:52.000
That's what the man told me that.

01:10:52.000 --> 01:10:54.000
He would give anything to Jaime.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:11:00.000
But he had hired a Chinese technician and he almost lost his job off of that.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:06.000
Everything there was white, it was in the heart of the black community.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:12.000
That's where all food related, dairy related technology jobs.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:13.000
Yeah.

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:19.000
The new PhD made you the, as far as you're aware, the first African American person,

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:24.000
the person of African descent to take a PhD in dairy science, perhaps.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:25.000
Yeah.

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:26.000
Ever.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:27.000
Yeah.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:35.000
As far as I know, because at Tuskegee, the man had a new mass, he got it from Wisconsin, I think.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:37.000
And most other places.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:45.000
And I did get a lot of letters from one college, I guess, maybe to Florida and Georgia.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:48.000
They wanted us to come right away.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:50.000
I'm going to teach you.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:51.000
Yeah.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.000
Not knowing that you're African American.

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:54.000
Yeah.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:55.000
No, no.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:57.000
These were African American schools.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:11:58.000
Oh, I see.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:02.000
But, of course, we couldn't because of miscellaneous laws.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:07.000
So you very consciously would not make, you would not have moved to the south in those years.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.000
No.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:10.000
Well, I don't think he could have had the job.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:12.000
I mean, these were state universities.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:13.000
Right.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:14.000
I think they were.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:15.000
Yeah.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:20.000
This was before the loving versus Virginia 1967.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:21.000
Yeah.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:22.000
Yeah.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:29.000
So we had, of course, 17 years of being illegal in some places.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:34.000
Not that we thought about it much, except in Virginia.

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:35.000
Yeah.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:36.000
Yeah.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:37.000
That was a difficulty.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:38.000
Yeah.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:39.000
Yeah.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:43.000
So you took a job in New York?

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:46.000
Yeah, I worked with Schaffield Falls.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:48.000
That was a big dick.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:49.000
No.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:52.000
This was after Columbus.

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:55.000
You would go into Schaffield farm after Massachusetts.

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:56.000
Yeah.

01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:57.000
Yeah.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:12:58.000
Yeah.

01:12:58.000 --> 01:12:59.000
Yeah.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:00.000
Yeah.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:01.000
Yeah.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:02.000
Yeah.

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:03.000
Yeah.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:04.000
Yeah.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:05.000
Yeah.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:06.000
Yeah.

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:07.000
That was after Massachusetts.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:08.000
Yeah.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:09.000
I took a job there.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:10.000
And, uh, at Columbia University?

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:11.000
At Columbia University.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:12.000
Yeah.

01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:13.000
Yes.

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:14.000
I went there and I had some jobs in the Department of Microbiology.

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:15.000
It was changing over.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:20.000
And they wanted people with a chemistry background.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And I had thought about this when I was going to Ohio State.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:31.000
If I couldn't get a job in Dura Technology, I can get one in organic chemistry.

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:35.000
And I took all the organic chemistry courses.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:43.000
And they asked me what I like to take a course in advanced physical chemistry.

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:48.000
And I could get a PhDs in chemistry.

01:13:48.000 --> 01:13:54.000
But I had made A's in all these advanced courses and physics.

01:13:54.000 --> 01:14:04.000
But I just thought that in advanced physical chemistry, I would need a little more math.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:07.000
And I didn't want to go take another math course.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:11.000
I had had calculus, but that was enough.

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:17.000
We had very poor training in mathematics in high school, elementary school.

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:19.000
We didn't have anything at all.

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:23.000
We didn't have people who could teach your square room.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:31.000
And I remember learning that from a book that one of the people that we were trading with,

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:33.000
her son died.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:36.000
And she told me I could have all of his book.

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:40.000
And I saw that white students in Virginia had physics.

01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:48.000
They had a math, a different math calculus, some calculus in high school.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:51.000
But I didn't have anything.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:54.000
Let's pause for just one second.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:56.000
We are back after a break for lunch.

01:14:56.000 --> 01:14:58.000
Thank you for a lovely lunch.

01:14:58.000 --> 01:15:00.000
It was delightful.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:05.000
And you have very kindly but firmly instructed me to say, Priscilla and Emmett.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:13.000
So with your permission, I will do that as we move through the second half of our interview.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:16.000
Priscilla, if you would, can you talk a little bit about some of the,

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:19.000
we're going to turn back to Columbus for a bit.

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:24.000
And there were a number of ramifications, I guess, that followed from your,

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:31.000
sort of becoming identified as a forceful advocate in the union context and perhaps otherwise.

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:36.000
Well, yes, I was a member of the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom,

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:40.000
which was founded by Jane Adams, World War I.

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:45.000
And it was a very congenial group of women.

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:52.000
There were maybe some men, but not, not in Columbus, but in New York there were.

01:15:52.000 --> 01:16:02.000
But that got Emmett into a little trouble because when he was being considered for a position at Ohio State,

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:06.000
which you hadn't applied for, they were just looking into it, right?

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:14.000
They were looking into it and their apartment had agreed that they would give me this assistant professor, John.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:15.000
Yeah.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:17.000
At Ohio State.

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:23.000
So, anyway, you were asked to visit with the FBI?

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:29.000
Yeah, he said, I mean, I'll tell you, and maybe this is wrong.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:30.000
Maybe I forgot.

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:32.000
He told me this is the head of the department.

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:34.000
Head of the department.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:35.000
Dr. Goog.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:37.000
Dr. Goog.

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:49.000
And he came to me and said that they weren't concerned about me, but they were concerned about some of your friends,

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:52.000
that it come to Iowa House.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:17:01.000
And the only thing I knew was that was a woman who was a friend of Priscilla's to some extent.

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:05.000
I don't know how much, but she had been to Iowa House.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:18.000
And I was down at Ohio State's, the University Hospital, and I met her with her husband, and she introduced me to a husband.

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:22.000
He was a doctor there, and in some position at the medical school.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:25.000
Well, I guess that was a...

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:26.000
Meer.

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:27.000
Yeah.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:28.000
I can't.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:29.000
I don't know.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:32.000
We never did figure out how to use that name.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:36.000
I don't use that name because I don't know that that would be true.

01:17:36.000 --> 01:17:37.000
I don't either.

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:40.000
But anyway, she...

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:46.000
I mean, I didn't really know what they were talking about.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:52.000
Well, I told them that I was not...

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:54.000
I didn't feel good.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:18:01.000
I wouldn't go and talk with the FBI, or CIA, or whatever they were.

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:03.000
I didn't know which it was.

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:08.000
But I told them that I would want to talk with either one of them.

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:11.000
So that was it.

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:26.000
And he said, well, you know, the University have that as a policy now that we have just been censored by the Association of University Professors.

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:32.000
And I told him that I belong to that organization.

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:38.000
And I wouldn't want to go and talk with any of that group.

01:18:38.000 --> 01:18:40.000
And he said, well, you can't get the job.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:43.000
I said, I don't want that job.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:46.000
That's what I have to do.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:53.000
But on a personal level, we had trouble swimming with the kids.

01:18:53.000 --> 01:18:57.000
And the swimming pools were closed.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:19:04.000
And so we used to go to this beautiful lake, called Lake Hope, which we really enjoyed going to.

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:06.000
That was great.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:15.000
So when we went out to Columbus to a family reunion, not having known there was any family in Columbus,

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:18.000
we went to Lake Hope with our granddaughter.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:21.000
And we had a fun time.

01:19:21.000 --> 01:19:28.000
And the other instances, when you would sort of, this was the episode you just recounted on, I'm presenting it was sort of a red scare kind of.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:32.000
Yes, that's what it was.

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:37.000
Were there other instances then and throughout the remainder of the 50s or 60s,

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:44.000
where those same kinds of pressures were brought to bear on you, this sort of out of the Cold War, I mean, red scare context?

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:47.000
Out of that. You mean racial only.

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:48.000
No, sorry.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:20:01.000
Were there other instances where some of the, were you encountered more concerns about you that came sort of focused through the lens of the red scare rather than through a racial?

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.000
Well, I also had a visit from the FBI.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:06.000
And I told them I was sorry.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:12.000
I was hanging clothes out in the yard where we lived.

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:16.000
I said I really wasn't available for a talk.

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:18.000
So that was the end of that.

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:24.000
But as far as jobs were concerned, it never was a problem for me.

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:25.000
No.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:30.000
And not in Columbus or in New York.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:31.000
So.

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:42.000
Dr. Bess, when you came to New York, ultimately with Columbia University, position.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:53.000
I'd love to have you just sketch in general terms some of your scholarly and academic work, because you would obviously have a long career as a professor and researcher.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:21:01.000
And I know our interview is not going to be about the science and all of that work, but I'd love to just have a basic description of all that work.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:04.000
Yeah, well, at Columbia.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:08.000
Now, they gave me a salary.

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:12.000
I guess it was came off a grant.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:25.000
And the only way that they could pay me is if we brought in enough money in grants to pay for my salary.

01:21:25.000 --> 01:21:32.000
And the man that I was working with, who was at that time, I think, a system professor.

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:36.000
And he had to pay a good portion of his salary.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:39.000
And the technician, we had to pay for.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:47.000
And we had to pay if they wanted to take a course that came out of our grants too.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:49.000
So we had to have grants.

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:54.000
So the idea was, I think the first year I was there, maybe it was the second.

01:21:54.000 --> 01:21:57.000
I don't remember precisely.

01:21:57.000 --> 01:22:06.000
We had made about five publications, big publications on the biosynthesis of Paturlin.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:25.000
We were also looking at different amino acids and how the two amino acids that were had benzene range.

01:22:25.000 --> 01:22:29.000
We were wondering how they formed, so we looked into that.

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:32.000
And we did publish a little note about it.

01:22:33.000 --> 01:22:39.000
But the man that I worked with, I wanted to publish the whole thing and probably do some more work.

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:44.000
He says, I don't, I spent all the money, so I can't go back.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:55.000
But I found out later that some of the people at Rockefeller Institute was also working on this.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:22:58.000
He says, they're going to read this.

01:22:58.000 --> 01:23:05.000
And if you write this paper, like you're going to write it, he says, it'll never get published.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:08.000
Because that is their field.

01:23:08.000 --> 01:23:09.000
And they were just turned.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:15.000
Now, I didn't know all of that politics was in to that type of work.

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:18.000
So I just went along with it.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:22.000
Okay, you just write in what you think is safe.

01:23:22.000 --> 01:23:24.000
And we were published that.

01:23:24.000 --> 01:23:34.000
So if you want to know what that was, you know, we had, they, no, no, this is it.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:40.000
I forget about all these amino acids and how many times do I know.

01:23:40.000 --> 01:23:46.000
But the two that are aromatics is tyrosine and phenylalanine.

01:23:46.000 --> 01:23:53.000
Now, we wanted to find out where they synthesized, like some more benzene range

01:23:53.000 --> 01:24:02.000
will be in synthesis, by this fungus we were working with.

01:24:02.000 --> 01:24:18.000
And I found out that tyrosine and phenylalanine probably same came from the same,

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:29.000
oh, what you were going to call that, from this, came from the same precursor, I guess I should call it,

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:31.000
came from the same precursor.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:38.000
And these people had it down that you had phenylalanine that was formed.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:42.000
And tyrosine was formed from the lalanine.

01:24:42.000 --> 01:24:49.000
Well, I put some radioactive material in some of the synthesis that we were doing.

01:24:49.000 --> 01:25:04.000
And I found out that more of the, the tyrosine had more of the radioactive carbons in it than phenylalanine.

01:25:04.000 --> 01:25:07.000
So it couldn't be coming from thin lalanine.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:18.000
But he decided that we didn't want to put that, we'd put it in as a kind of a temporary note that we noted that.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:27.000
And so a few weeks later, I think it was two people who had gotten the note, not the Nobel Prize.

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:36.000
I don't know what they had, but anyway, they had gotten some, a lot of rewards for what they had done.

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:43.000
Maybe they got some kind of a prize, but he said they would never approve of this.

01:25:43.000 --> 01:25:46.000
So we published it his way and that got published.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:54.000
So that year we published five different papers and enough to get us a lot of grant for us the next year.

01:25:54.000 --> 01:25:58.000
So that we worked against.

01:25:58.000 --> 01:26:06.000
But you weren't completely free to publish anything you wanted stuff.

01:26:06.000 --> 01:26:19.000
And I think three or four months later, they republished their work and they published it and said they came from a common precursor.

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:24.000
But they didn't come at the same sequence.

01:26:24.000 --> 01:26:32.000
Both of them came at different points in the development of the organism.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:36.000
We wanted to say that too, but he wouldn't put it in.

01:26:36.000 --> 01:26:42.000
And he was putting most of the money into the research I was doing.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:52.000
Because at that time, I was just postdoc at that time.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:27:04.000
Did that reflect that I was straightforward academic politics, not racial politics?

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:07.000
Is that correct or not? You don't know.

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:12.000
I think it's academic. I think it's that.

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:15.000
These other folks you were working with at Columbia were white.

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:19.000
Yeah, they were white.

01:27:19.000 --> 01:27:25.000
This grew down at...

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:27.000
I'm trying to...

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:29.000
Rockestella Institute.

01:27:29.000 --> 01:27:31.000
They had much more money than we did.

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:47.000
And they had a lot of postdocs and they had a lot of people who had worked there for a long time with those people at the Rockestella.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:50.000
So they kind of had a corner on that.

01:27:50.000 --> 01:27:53.000
And they would look at us as Putin then.

01:27:53.000 --> 01:28:01.000
So what they probably would say to us that you haven't done enough research on this to make that statement.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:05.000
So they went back and there were three different groups.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:09.000
I don't can't recall what all three of them were.

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:19.000
But they agreed that they both would say that they had redone the work and they published again of hard work.

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:22.000
And it was the same thing. I wanted to post.

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:25.000
I never got a chance.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:34.000
How did your lives as activists on the question of racial equality?

01:28:34.000 --> 01:28:40.000
How did that unfold in after you settled in New York in the mid 1950s?

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:44.000
Because the Little Rocks 57...

01:28:44.000 --> 01:28:46.000
Hello, my name is the year before that.

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:53.000
The Little Rocks 57 Greensboro kicks off the sort of major white open demonstration phase of the movement.

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:56.000
What was the pattern of your involvement across those years?

01:28:56.000 --> 01:28:58.000
Do you want to describe that?

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:01.000
Well, let's see.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:06.000
Our daughter was going to public school.

01:29:06.000 --> 01:29:10.000
This was just part and our personal lives.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:15.000
And she was in kindergarten.

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:20.000
And the school was a very large class with two teachers.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:31.000
And we had the opportunity to send her to private school to an ethical culture school.

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:38.000
The Fielsen School, which was in a rural part, not so rural, but you know,

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:45.000
a less urban section of New York City, Riverdale, New York.

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:52.000
And a lot of nice campus and good teachers and so forth.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:57.000
Now, I was not in favor of leaving the public school system.

01:29:57.000 --> 01:30:04.000
But I also knew how Emmett felt having gone to a one-room segregated school

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:07.000
where the teachers rarely finished the school year.

01:30:07.000 --> 01:30:16.000
And he had only one teacher that he really connected with in his whole life there.

01:30:16.000 --> 01:30:19.000
So I would certainly defer.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:33.000
And I was convinced of that when I met May Mallory, who was a colleague of Robert Williams in North Carolina, right?

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:39.000
May Mallory was a real activist.

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:48.000
And I happened to be sitting with her at lunch at a meeting on the New York City Public School system.

01:30:48.000 --> 01:30:51.000
And I told her my dilemma.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:54.000
And she said, no dilemma.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:59.000
You just send your child whether that child will get the best education.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:02.000
And she said, you can keep on fighting for what you believe in.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:05.000
It doesn't mean you won't.

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:10.000
And so that convinced me that I would defer to Emmett.

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:13.000
And so we did with our three kids.

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:25.000
But Emmett, I mean, we, I think you, more than I actually got involved in that business with the integration of the middle schools in Washington Heights.

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:26.000
Yeah.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:29.000
I could go to the walk-out.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:42.000
There was also a Freedom School that we had where the children went in a Methodist church in Riverdale, or Kingsbridge.

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:55.000
And then when there was a big Brownsville issue, Ocean Hill Brownsville, we tried to keep the local school open.

01:31:55.000 --> 01:32:09.000
Not with the regular teachers, but the teachers who were willing to support community-based school boards.

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:17.000
So that even though I was a mother in a private school, I was still involved.

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:24.000
And so, and Emmett also, I mean, I think you were on the front page of the Daily News for ticketing somewhere.

01:32:24.000 --> 01:32:26.000
I know we never had that deal.

01:32:26.000 --> 01:32:29.000
You feel like a tank up with sugar.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:35.000
And yes, they filmed our car tank up with sugar.

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:38.000
And we had to have that pumped out.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:39.000
Washed out.

01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:41.000
Very angry people.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:45.000
This was in Washington Heights.

01:32:45.000 --> 01:32:49.000
About these middle schools.

01:32:49.000 --> 01:32:56.000
We were trying to, they had three junior high school, and we were trying to get them to integrate them.

01:32:56.000 --> 01:33:01.000
Each one of them takes so many lives, so many lives.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:04.000
Get a kind of balance at the time.

01:33:04.000 --> 01:33:10.000
And they were in a good geographic area where they were fairly close together.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:11.000
Yeah.

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:12.000
Nobody would have to travel.

01:33:12.000 --> 01:33:13.000
Travel, pause.

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:14.000
Very long distance.

01:33:14.000 --> 01:33:21.000
Some of the blacks would go here, some go here, and some would go in home district.

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:24.000
And white students would come into that too.

01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:34.000
And we thought we had worked it out, but we came back and we found out that everybody who was supporting us had gotten fired or something.

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:36.000
The principal.

01:33:36.000 --> 01:33:37.000
Is it there?

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:38.000
Yeah.

01:33:38.000 --> 01:33:39.000
Yeah.

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:41.000
So it was bad times.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:48.000
So this would have been what years, your years?

01:33:48.000 --> 01:33:49.000
Yeah, really.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:52.000
Well, when did Mitchy start?

01:33:52.000 --> 01:33:56.000
It feels to me because they used to come and tell me you don't sense your kids that.

01:33:56.000 --> 01:33:59.000
Yeah, we do get that.

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:04.000
Well, we were, were we living in, we were living in...

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:06.000
High and high in Assistan.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:09.000
Yeah, we were living in...

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:13.000
I think we were living in, it would be in the early 60s.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:14.000
Yes, early 60s.

01:34:14.000 --> 01:34:17.000
Yeah, we were living in Kauaap.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:18.000
Kauaap?

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:19.000
Yeah.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:21.000
Would your children ever come back into the New York City Public Schools?

01:34:21.000 --> 01:34:22.000
No, no.

01:34:22.000 --> 01:34:23.000
Okay.

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:24.000
No, they went all the way through.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:25.000
Yeah.

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:32.000
I know, Dr. Bassett, that you had a very interesting engagement with the planning for the March in Washington.

01:34:32.000 --> 01:34:33.000
Yeah.

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:39.000
But I guess I was kind of recruited by...

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:40.000
What's his name?

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:41.000
Fire rusted?

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:42.000
No.

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:43.000
No, Bob.

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:47.000
Our neighbor, he was a neighbor and friend, Bob Lewis.

01:34:47.000 --> 01:34:48.000
Bob Lewis.

01:34:48.000 --> 01:34:50.000
I really recruited him.

01:34:50.000 --> 01:34:57.000
Well, I think that he probably was recruited by...

01:34:57.000 --> 01:35:01.000
said...

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:04.000
Oh, the one that supported Martin Luther King.

01:35:04.000 --> 01:35:06.000
He used to come up every week.

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:07.000
You mean Stan Levis...

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:08.000
Stan Levis.

01:35:08.000 --> 01:35:09.000
Stan Levis.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:11.000
Yeah, I keep thinking of him.

01:35:11.000 --> 01:35:12.000
Stan.

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:13.000
Who had been in...

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:14.000
In friendship this was.

01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:16.000
In friendship, yeah.

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:17.000
In friendship.

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:19.000
Yeah, I was in that.

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:22.000
And when I went into that,

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:30.000
Bob Rustin had left this group and had gone to Africa to try to stop the French bomb.

01:35:30.000 --> 01:35:32.000
I never saw him at a meeting.

01:35:32.000 --> 01:35:33.000
Tester.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:34.000
Tester.

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:35.000
And when I...

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:37.000
He came back to the country.

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:44.000
We were at a meeting at the Apollo Theater in Harlem.

01:35:44.000 --> 01:35:47.000
And that's when they...

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:53.000
We turned it back over to April of Brand-Op.

01:35:53.000 --> 01:35:58.000
And he had all the people he had chosen to work with.

01:35:58.000 --> 01:36:01.000
I guess in ACP and so forth.

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:03.000
All the churches.

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:05.000
We turned all of that over to him.

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:08.000
But you had recruited a lot of buses.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:13.000
I remember there was a threshold that he wanted before he would commit himself, right?

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:15.000
Well, we think we had enough...

01:36:15.000 --> 01:36:17.000
100,000 people.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:18.000
Yeah.

01:36:18.000 --> 01:36:20.000
And I think they...

01:36:20.000 --> 01:36:21.000
That was in friendship.

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:23.000
I mean, him and it was a part of that.

01:36:23.000 --> 01:36:24.000
Yeah, just a part of that.

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:25.000
You went to Washington?

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:26.000
Yes.

01:36:26.000 --> 01:36:27.000
Yes, we did go.

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:28.000
Yeah.

01:36:28.000 --> 01:36:29.000
Yeah.

01:36:29.000 --> 01:36:30.000
Can you share your...

01:36:30.000 --> 01:36:34.000
And we had been to the Prayer Pilgrimage also.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:37.000
And a lot of people don't remember that.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:39.000
But that was very moving.

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:40.000
The Prayer Pilgrimage.

01:36:40.000 --> 01:36:42.000
Yes, that was very moving.

01:36:42.000 --> 01:36:43.000
Can you describe it?

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:44.000
That's great.

01:36:44.000 --> 01:36:50.000
Well, we had our two children with us at that.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:51.000
Yeah.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:52.000
Did we drive down there?

01:36:52.000 --> 01:36:53.000
I think so.

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:54.000
I think Buzzie...

01:36:54.000 --> 01:36:55.000
Where's that?

01:36:55.000 --> 01:36:59.000
No, I don't think so.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:02.000
You know, I get a little...

01:37:02.000 --> 01:37:05.000
It was by the reflecting pool.

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:10.000
And Dr. King was the first time that I had ever heard him speak.

01:37:10.000 --> 01:37:12.000
And that was very moving.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:15.000
And that's what I remember.

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:19.000
Now, that was when you went down from Columbus.

01:37:19.000 --> 01:37:20.000
And the Fred?

01:37:20.000 --> 01:37:21.000
No, no.

01:37:21.000 --> 01:37:22.000
This was...

01:37:22.000 --> 01:37:23.000
This was...

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:26.000
We were living in Bramsew in Brooklyn.

01:37:26.000 --> 01:37:27.000
Yeah.

01:37:27.000 --> 01:37:31.000
When we came back, we had a hard time finding an apartment in New York City.

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:40.000
So this was what, 1956, right after the bus board cop, which is real debut, so to speak, on

01:37:40.000 --> 01:37:41.000
the public...

01:37:41.000 --> 01:37:42.000
Yeah.

01:37:42.000 --> 01:37:46.000
Is that the instance where the landlord changed your box?

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:50.000
Oh, that happened just before we were married.

01:37:50.000 --> 01:37:57.000
I think we just moved in not ourselves, but we moved in some blankets and things.

01:37:57.000 --> 01:37:58.000
Yeah.

01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:03.000
I don't know what we thought we were going to sleep on.

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:05.000
Well, we had some more.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:07.000
We had some other things.

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:12.000
But we just put enough and add a claim to the apartment.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:15.000
And when we went back, yes, sure.

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:16.000
The door was locked.

01:38:16.000 --> 01:38:17.000
I went back, yeah.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:19.000
You went back and door was locked?

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:20.000
Yeah.

01:38:20.000 --> 01:38:21.000
I went there, it was locked.

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:22.000
Yeah.

01:38:22.000 --> 01:38:23.000
The key didn't work.

01:38:23.000 --> 01:38:25.000
It was quite a shock.

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:26.000
A shock?

01:38:26.000 --> 01:38:28.000
I went over and talked to the man.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:31.000
And he says, well, I want to give you the barber.

01:38:31.000 --> 01:38:33.000
He says, I want to give you your money back.

01:38:33.000 --> 01:38:36.000
I said, but no, that's not what we want.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:38.000
We want to have a party.

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:42.000
And he says, well, I was told not to give it to you.

01:38:42.000 --> 01:38:44.000
Yeah, the key.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:46.000
We did have some housing things.

01:38:46.000 --> 01:38:56.000
But to finish up on the education, both of us tried to blend our work lives

01:38:56.000 --> 01:38:59.000
with our activism.

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:06.000
And I was, I participated in the council on interracial books for children,

01:39:06.000 --> 01:39:12.000
which encouraged publishers to publish books by African-American

01:39:12.000 --> 01:39:15.000
or as we used the word black.

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:21.000
And I still do, but African-American authors and illustrators

01:39:21.000 --> 01:39:25.000
and also popularized the books.

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:31.000
And that was, you know, a very, very good way to,

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:35.000
because I was a children's library.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:40.000
And what about you being through all your professional work

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:43.000
and as a librarian that you're telling us about?

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:49.000
Yes, we're all developing curriculum, book collection, everything.

01:39:49.000 --> 01:39:52.000
Yes, I really was very key.

01:39:52.000 --> 01:39:54.000
And I believe also related to the theme of your master's thesis

01:39:54.000 --> 01:39:56.000
when you got your LLS.

01:39:56.000 --> 01:39:57.000
What?

01:39:57.000 --> 01:40:00.000
Also related to your master's thesis theme when you got your MLS.

01:40:00.000 --> 01:40:02.000
Yes, yes.

01:40:02.000 --> 01:40:06.000
Yeah, I was urged to publish it.

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:12.000
But at the time, I didn't think it was appropriate for me as a white woman

01:40:12.000 --> 01:40:15.000
to publish it.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:21.000
You know, I was, I was having a certain advantage in getting that published

01:40:21.000 --> 01:40:25.000
that white scheme privilege.

01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:28.000
And that I really didn't think that was appropriate.

01:40:28.000 --> 01:40:32.000
And so I don't know that anybody's ever published anything.

01:40:32.000 --> 01:40:35.000
But I did go back and many of the books are out of print.

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:37.000
And I'm sad about that.

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:38.000
Yeah.

01:40:38.000 --> 01:40:45.000
Because the whole theme of that was the rejection of a child's first language

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:57.000
when he or she goes into the formal education has a very alienating effect.

01:40:57.000 --> 01:40:58.000
Absolutely.

01:40:58.000 --> 01:41:22.000
I think I was a flying for a job which I really didn't want.

01:41:22.000 --> 01:41:25.000
But they wanted me to apply for that too.

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:30.000
And I was really, they tried to do right by me.

01:41:30.000 --> 01:41:36.000
Are the other parts of your long pattern of engagement with progressive struggle

01:41:36.000 --> 01:41:38.000
that are related?

01:41:38.000 --> 01:41:44.000
Because of course, the Vietnam War would become a focus of your activism in the late 60s

01:41:44.000 --> 01:41:49.000
but staying save the front half of the 60s where there are other things that stand out

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:57.000
about the community of progressive activism in New York and your connections to that community.

01:41:57.000 --> 01:41:58.000
The early 60s.

01:41:58.000 --> 01:42:05.000
I guess I reconnected with the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:13.000
and how I ever saved it, I don't know, but I gave a talk on war toys, I remember.

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:16.000
So that was certainly a part of war toys.

01:42:16.000 --> 01:42:19.000
What was your third year of war toys?

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:20.000
I was very important to me.

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:23.000
I'm sorry, you met children's toys, war toys.

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:24.000
Yes, war toys.

01:42:24.000 --> 01:42:26.000
Yes, war toys.

01:42:26.000 --> 01:42:30.000
What else was happening in the early 60s?

01:42:30.000 --> 01:42:39.000
They didn't want us to at, where there's 33, hillside.

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:41.000
Oh, Fort George Avenue?

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:42.000
Yeah.

01:42:42.000 --> 01:42:45.000
They didn't want us to give our meetings inside of them.

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:49.000
Oh, that's right, that's one reason that I wanted to leave.

01:42:49.000 --> 01:42:53.000
We were in a cooperative, Mitchelum, cooperative.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:43:07.000
This was a state program that subsidized, it wasn't low income, but it was middle income families, apartments.

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:11.000
And we moved in there and it was a wonderful place.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:18.000
We, in advance to moving, we had meetings and there was a cooperative board.

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:28.000
And we designed the playground that we wanted to have, you know, using more modern equipment and so forth.

01:43:28.000 --> 01:43:39.000
And we were there and we did have some meetings of the Upper Manhattan Committee for Equal Rights.

01:43:39.000 --> 01:43:40.000
Yes.

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:41.000
Right?

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:57.000
And the board, of which I was a member, decided that it was just getting to be overwhelming this whole situation with the lack of change in the South.

01:43:57.000 --> 01:44:01.000
That they really wanted to take a step back.

01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:07.000
And it wasn't just the South, the North too, because we were involved with the public schools, you and I.

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:14.000
So it wasn't just us because there were several other people in the building who were active with the group.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:21.000
But they decided by majority vote not to allow the meetings there anymore.

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:22.000
Yeah.

01:44:22.000 --> 01:44:28.000
So at that point, I heard about another apartment and we moved.

01:44:28.000 --> 01:44:30.000
We abandoned the struggle.

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:36.000
That was the top one that you made that move.

01:44:36.000 --> 01:44:42.000
That was 61, we moved into the co-op.

01:44:42.000 --> 01:44:45.000
It was about 64.

01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:46.000
About five.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:47.000
Yeah.

01:44:47.000 --> 01:44:50.000
It was about 64, I think, before we went to Sweden.

01:44:50.000 --> 01:44:51.000
Yeah.

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:57.000
Did you, in New York, did you ever have a occasion to hear Malcolm X?

01:44:57.000 --> 01:44:59.000
Oh, I used to go here all the time.

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:00.000
Did you?

01:45:00.000 --> 01:45:01.000
Yeah.

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:04.000
And I remember that in the sidewalk once.

01:45:04.000 --> 01:45:05.000
I went.

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:06.000
With whom?

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:07.000
Who was that?

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:10.000
Who was poverty in America?

01:45:10.000 --> 01:45:11.000
Yeah.

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:12.000
Yeah.

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:13.000
He was on the board.

01:45:13.000 --> 01:45:15.000
Well, anyway, it'll come to me.

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:18.000
You know, Michael Harrington, yeah.

01:45:18.000 --> 01:45:23.000
I was talking with Michael Harrington and Malcolm X.

01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:28.000
And we got into a three-way conversation.

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:34.000
What do you remember about the occasions of going to here at Malcolm X?

01:45:34.000 --> 01:45:35.000
Did you?

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:36.000
You never went.

01:45:36.000 --> 01:45:37.000
I didn't.

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:38.000
No.

01:45:38.000 --> 01:45:41.000
I went three or four times.

01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:52.000
And I guess, after he had broken, you saw the violence kind of hiding it.

01:45:52.000 --> 01:45:53.000
I didn't go.

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:56.000
I guess we went for a walk that morning.

01:45:56.000 --> 01:45:57.000
You got shot.

01:45:57.000 --> 01:45:59.000
Yeah, we lived not far away.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:00.000
Yeah.

01:46:00.000 --> 01:46:01.000
We weren't there.

01:46:01.000 --> 01:46:08.000
We never went to them when they took on religious light.

01:46:08.000 --> 01:46:15.000
Well, when I remember you're going, I went with what's, what's, what's, what's, what's

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:17.000
a Glanders' husband?

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:19.000
Oh, oh, okay.

01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:20.000
Yeah.

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:21.000
All right.

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:22.000
You knew who we went.

01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:23.000
Yeah, that's right.

01:46:23.000 --> 01:46:24.000
Yeah.

01:46:24.000 --> 01:46:26.000
I went to three or four.

01:46:26.000 --> 01:46:27.000
Yeah.

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:28.000
There are speeches in Harlem.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:29.000
Yeah.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:30.000
I don't know just where they were.

01:46:30.000 --> 01:46:35.000
But it looked like someone went in the Harlem, uh, Army building.

01:46:35.000 --> 01:46:36.000
Yeah.

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:37.000
In the Army?

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:38.000
Yes.

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:39.000
In the Army?

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:40.000
Yes.

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:41.000
Yeah, Army.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:49.200
Did you, um, obviously you would, you would take up activism or roles as activists in relation

01:46:49.200 --> 01:46:50.200
to the war.

01:46:50.200 --> 01:46:58.120
I'm wondering, say, by, we were just alluding to Malcolm X's assassination in what, the

01:46:58.120 --> 01:47:01.500
war was in the last two or four or five, I guess.

01:47:01.500 --> 01:47:02.500
Yeah.

01:47:02.500 --> 01:47:09.620
And of course by the 68, the war was really heated up by the Kennedy and Dr. King or killed

01:47:09.620 --> 01:47:10.620
that summer.

01:47:10.620 --> 01:47:17.060
I'm just wondering kind of how you were taking stock of the struggle, if you will, by the

01:47:17.060 --> 01:47:21.640
late sixties and from, from the perspective where you were in your lives.

01:47:21.640 --> 01:47:26.940
Well, I mean, that's when I first went to Colombia, didn't.

01:47:26.940 --> 01:47:29.940
I went to Columbia.

01:47:29.940 --> 01:47:32.940
Were you out of Newark when the Newark rebellion happened?

01:47:32.940 --> 01:47:34.940
We were in Sweden.

01:47:34.940 --> 01:47:37.940
You were, that's right.

01:47:37.940 --> 01:47:40.940
No, this is...

01:47:40.940 --> 01:47:44.940
I'm a state at ortho, two years.

01:47:44.940 --> 01:47:50.940
But you went to New Jersey College of Medicine and Dentistry after the Newark riots.

01:47:50.940 --> 01:47:51.940
Rebellion.

01:47:51.940 --> 01:47:52.940
After you came back from Sweden?

01:47:52.940 --> 01:47:53.940
Yeah.

01:47:53.940 --> 01:47:55.940
I'm just...

01:47:55.940 --> 01:47:57.940
I'm sorry.

01:47:57.940 --> 01:48:00.940
But you didn't go straight there, did you?

01:48:00.940 --> 01:48:01.940
No.

01:48:01.940 --> 01:48:04.940
No, you went to ortho-pharmaceutical.

01:48:04.940 --> 01:48:06.940
Yeah, I built a lab.

01:48:06.940 --> 01:48:07.940
Oh, boy.

01:48:07.940 --> 01:48:10.940
But he didn't want to stay there.

01:48:10.940 --> 01:48:13.940
Was it worth a part of Johnson & Johnson?

01:48:13.940 --> 01:48:14.940
Yeah.

01:48:14.940 --> 01:48:16.940
It's a part of Johnson & Johnson.

01:48:16.940 --> 01:48:17.940
And...

01:48:17.940 --> 01:48:22.940
I want to say about Sweden, but please tell me about what factors led you not to want to stay at?

01:48:22.940 --> 01:48:24.940
Johnson & Johnson.

01:48:24.940 --> 01:48:25.940
Ah.

01:48:25.940 --> 01:48:31.940
Let me see.

01:48:31.940 --> 01:48:34.940
Well, I guess.

01:48:34.940 --> 01:48:37.940
Let me see.

01:48:37.940 --> 01:48:38.940
What?

01:48:38.940 --> 01:48:41.940
Testing products, some of that?

01:48:41.940 --> 01:48:43.940
Yeah, I was testing.

01:48:43.940 --> 01:48:45.940
No, not you.

01:48:45.940 --> 01:48:51.940
When they tested in other, in poor communities in the world,

01:48:51.940 --> 01:48:55.940
they tested some of their products.

01:48:55.940 --> 01:48:57.940
I just vaguely remember this.

01:48:57.940 --> 01:49:01.940
I saw a lot of things that I didn't like.

01:49:01.940 --> 01:49:12.940
But, you know, they used to buy blood here, buy blood there, and some blood.

01:49:12.940 --> 01:49:15.940
You knew that they bought blood all over the place.

01:49:15.940 --> 01:49:19.940
But sometimes they'd invite with Johnson & Johnson's name.

01:49:19.940 --> 01:49:27.940
They bought it through another front group.

01:49:27.940 --> 01:49:32.940
And you had all of that going on there.

01:49:32.940 --> 01:49:39.940
And when you compare those hours with some of the other places,

01:49:39.940 --> 01:49:42.940
we weren't paid very much.

01:49:42.940 --> 01:49:47.940
So when I got the job at New Jersey, they paid more than ortho.

01:49:47.940 --> 01:49:51.940
Everybody was happy out there because they got a big set.

01:49:51.940 --> 01:49:56.940
But they offered you free tuition for your daughter.

01:49:56.940 --> 01:49:57.940
Yeah.

01:49:57.940 --> 01:50:05.940
And other, they gave him a big raise and he said, no, I told you I'm not coming back.

01:50:05.940 --> 01:50:07.940
And that's what I mean.

01:50:07.940 --> 01:50:09.940
So that was them.

01:50:09.940 --> 01:50:10.940
Well, yeah.

01:50:10.940 --> 01:50:14.940
I'd love to hear you, um, okay, let's pause for a minute here.

01:50:14.940 --> 01:50:17.940
Okay, we're back to break.

01:50:17.940 --> 01:50:26.940
Just while we were off there for a minute, there's an interesting aspect of the recruitment at the New Jersey College of Medicine and Dentistry, I guess.

01:50:26.940 --> 01:50:35.940
And their effort to reach out to you because, as I understand, the college had not was standing there was in Newark,

01:50:35.940 --> 01:50:40.940
which had recently experienced this tremendous people.

01:50:40.940 --> 01:50:45.940
You, African Americans on their entire faculty.

01:50:45.940 --> 01:50:46.940
That's right.

01:50:46.940 --> 01:50:47.940
Yeah.

01:50:47.940 --> 01:50:53.940
Yeah, they wanted you and they wanted you to serve on the admissions department.

01:50:53.940 --> 01:50:58.940
All of these things that didn't help you were my future research work.

01:50:58.940 --> 01:51:02.940
I guess that was one of the things that kind of eat at you.

01:51:02.940 --> 01:51:09.940
It used to be the doctors were on the black doctors were on this, but they could easily get out.

01:51:09.940 --> 01:51:10.940
I got an emergency.

01:51:10.940 --> 01:51:12.940
I have the surgeries today.

01:51:12.940 --> 01:51:15.940
And who they're going to call me?

01:51:15.940 --> 01:51:21.940
So I was covered from probably ten, five or six different people.

01:51:21.940 --> 01:51:22.940
They never showed up.

01:51:22.940 --> 01:51:24.940
They told me.

01:51:24.940 --> 01:51:25.940
Yeah.

01:51:25.940 --> 01:51:31.940
I'd love to have you describe your year in Sweden.

01:51:31.940 --> 01:51:33.940
Could you do a better job?

01:51:33.940 --> 01:51:38.940
Well, for the family it was really pretty exciting.

01:51:38.940 --> 01:51:40.940
Yeah, I thought so.

01:51:40.940 --> 01:51:55.940
We went across the ocean and an ocean liner to Norway and then visited a friend from Rockefeller Institute

01:51:55.940 --> 01:51:59.940
and his wife who had been Emmett's technician.

01:51:59.940 --> 01:52:12.940
And from there in Trondheim we went by train down to Opsala and we were, you know, everything just went so nicely.

01:52:12.940 --> 01:52:15.940
We had to wait a while to get in the car.

01:52:15.940 --> 01:52:17.940
We had to wait a while.

01:52:17.940 --> 01:52:18.940
Yes, we had to wait.

01:52:18.940 --> 01:52:20.940
But that was all right.

01:52:20.940 --> 01:52:22.940
The nice thing was going down.

01:52:22.940 --> 01:52:24.940
We stopped off in order.

01:52:24.940 --> 01:52:25.940
Yeah.

01:52:25.940 --> 01:52:33.940
And we didn't read the schedule correctly and there was no place to spend the night.

01:52:33.940 --> 01:52:36.940
And the station master took us into his house.

01:52:36.940 --> 01:52:37.940
Yeah.

01:52:37.940 --> 01:52:39.940
Imagine that.

01:52:39.940 --> 01:52:41.940
So that was very nice.

01:52:41.940 --> 01:52:47.940
Anyway, we found it a quite a welcoming environment.

01:52:47.940 --> 01:52:50.940
And you worked with Dr. Arna Tisalus?

01:52:50.940 --> 01:52:51.940
Tisalus?

01:52:51.940 --> 01:52:52.940
Yeah.

01:52:52.940 --> 01:52:53.940
Tisalus.

01:52:53.940 --> 01:52:55.940
Yeah, I really didn't work with him.

01:52:55.940 --> 01:53:00.940
He didn't come to the lab at all.

01:53:00.940 --> 01:53:01.940
It works his lab.

01:53:01.940 --> 01:53:04.940
But I talked with him a lot.

01:53:04.940 --> 01:53:11.940
And he had had other professors from Columbia, a doctor-cabinet.

01:53:11.940 --> 01:53:14.940
And they were great friends.

01:53:14.940 --> 01:53:19.940
So I guess I got all of those recommendations.

01:53:19.940 --> 01:53:23.940
And so I got in very easy.

01:53:23.940 --> 01:53:24.940
That's positive.

01:53:24.940 --> 01:53:25.940
Just a second.

01:53:25.940 --> 01:53:26.940
Long.

01:53:26.940 --> 01:53:27.940
